Recently, single-server private information retrieval (PIR) with preprocessing has been suggested to achieve sublinear online server computation, with query-independent information precomputed and stored by the server/client. While state-of-the-art preprocessing solutions, such as FrodoPIR and SimplePIR, fail to achieve sublinear online time, they are fairly simple and concretely efficient. However, these schemes are inefficient for database updates, requiring each client to redownload a “new” portion of the hint for any updates. Moreover, they suffer from high client storage requirements and online communication, which is client-unfriendly. In this paper, we propose a more client friendly and updatable single-server PIR with preprocessing. In particular, we define the notion of Symmetric key-based Simulatable Fully Homomorphic Encryption (\(\mathsf {SS}\mbox{-}\mathsf {FHE}\)). Specifically, it is an FHE scheme with an extra property we call simulatability, which allows simulation of a qualified homomorphic ciphertext without sampling a secret key. Based on this concept, we show how to construct a generic PIR with preprocessing that provides native support for database updates and eliminates the need for client storage. Furthermore, we offer an implementation of the TFHE-based instantiation on Ubuntu, which shows the feasibility of our scheme. Although the instantiation is limited to 1-bit databases and and incurs higher online time, our approach lays the groundwork for more practical and scalable PIR solutions.